[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "French Tarrasch Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ This is known as the French Defense. It is a favorite of many players who have an affinity for closed or semi-open positions. }
2. d4
{ White occupies the center with two pawns. If Black plays passively now, White's central mass will become very dangerous. }
2... d5
{ Black strikes back in the center. Now White has a few different options to choose from. }
3. Nd2
{ This is known as the Tarrasch Variation and is one of the main lines along with 3.Nc3. The main idea behind this move is to guard the e4-pawn while maintaining the mobility of the c-pawn. The downside of this move is that the knight would be slightly more active on c3. That is why the knight usually aims for f3 or b3 in many variations of the Tarrasch. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Closed Variation"]
[Black "Closed Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6
{ This is known as the Closed Variation because it leads to a fairly closed position after White's next move: e5. White has very good play here because of the mobility of his c-pawn. }
4. e5 { White advances his center pawn and wins a tempo on Black's knight. }
4... Nfd7 { Black's knight retreats to d7, where it can support a c5 advance. }
5. Bd3
{ White develops onto the ideal b1-h7 diagonal where it can aid an attack against Black's kingside. }
5... c5
{ This is Black's only reasonable choice. Black's whole plan is based on playing against White's fixed center pawns. }
6. c3
{ This demonstrates one of the key points of the French Tarrasch compared to the 3. Nc3 lines: the mobility of the c-pawn. Because his knight is on d2, White is able to advance his c-pawn to c3, where it lends his pawn on d4 extra support. }
6... Nc6
{ This is the main line. Black continues to apply pressure to White's pawn on d4. }
7. Ne2
{ White supports his pawn on d4 while maintaining the possibility of moving his f-pawn. }
7... cxd4
{ This is the most popular choice at Black's disposal, releasing the tension in the center. }
8. cxd4 Qb6 { Qb6 puts pressure on d4, but after Nf3, White is fine. } 9. Nf3
{ We have transposed to a previous position where Black is choosing between Bb4+ and f6. }
*

