[White "Closed Variation"]
[Black "Closed Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6
{ This is known as the Closed Variation because it leads to a fairly closed position after White's next move: e5. White has very good play here because of the mobility of his c-pawn. }
4. e5 { White advances his center pawn and wins a tempo on Black's knight. }
4... Nfd7 { Black's knight retreats to d7, where it can support a c5 advance. }
5. Bd3
{ White develops onto the ideal b1-h7 diagonal where it can aid an attack against Black's kingside. }
5... c5
{ This is Black's only reasonable choice. Black's whole plan is based on playing against White's fixed center pawns. }
6. c3
{ This demonstrates one of the key points of the French Tarrasch compared to the 3. Nc3 lines: the mobility of the c-pawn. Because his knight is on d2, White is able to advance his c-pawn to c3, where it lends his pawn on d4 extra support. }
6... b6
{ This move is also playable. Black's goal is to exchange off his bad light-squared bishop for White's good light-squared bishop. }
7. Ne2
{ White will get very strong development because Black's plan is somewhat slow. }
7... Ba6 { Black offers the trade of bishops. } 8. Bxa6
{ White trades the bishops. } 8... Nxa6 9. O-O Nc7
{ Black realizes that his knight is a poor piece on a6 and brings it back to c7. }
10. Nf4 c4 { Black locks up the position completely. } 11. Qg4
{ White's play on the kingside is quite strong and this will bother Black for the rest of the game. Also, Black cannot play f6 here because the e6-pawn hangs. }
