{ This is the most popular choice at Black's disposal, releasing the tension in the center. }
8. cxd4 f6 { This is the main line. Black begins to undermine the e5-pawn. } 9.
exf6 { White takes on f6, creating a Black weakness on e6. } 9... Nxf6
{ This is the main move, bringing the knight to a more active square. } 10. Nf3
{ This is a common landing place for the knight. From f3 it eyes the hole on e5 and lends the d4-pawn some support. }
10... Bd6 11. O-O { White brings his king to safety. } 11... Qc7
{ Black wants to prevent Bf4, which trades the dark-squared bishops } 12. Bg5
O-O { e5 is met by Nc3 ! } 13. Rc1
{ White brings his rook into play and pins the c6-knight. } 13... Ng4 14. h3
{ Now play becomes quite exciting. } 14... Rxf3
{ Black sacrifices the exchange ! } 15. hxg4
{ White should take on g4 because gxf3 is too dangerous. The position is imbalanced but White is better. }
