1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6
{ This is known as the Closed Variation because it leads to a fairly closed position after White's next move: e5. White has very good play here because of the mobility of his c-pawn. }
4. e5 { White advances his center pawn and wins a tempo on Black's knight. }
4... Nfd7 { Black's knight retreats to d7, where it can support a c5 advance. }
5. Bd3
{ White develops onto the ideal b1-h7 diagonal where it can aid an attack against Black's kingside. }
5... c5
{ This is Black's only reasonable choice. Black's whole plan is based on playing against White's fixed center pawns. }
6. c3
{ This demonstrates one of the key points of the French Tarrasch compared to the 3. Nc3 lines: the mobility of the c-pawn. Because his knight is on d2, White is able to advance his c-pawn to c3, where it lends his pawn on d4 extra support. }
6... Nc6
{ This is the main line. Black continues to apply pressure to White's pawn on d4. }
7. Ne2
{ White supports his pawn on d4 while maintaining the possibility of moving his f-pawn. }
7... Qb6
{ This is the main alternative to taking immediately on d4. Black continues to apply pressure on the d4-pawn. }
8. Nf3
{ White frees a diagonal for his dark-squared bishop and gives his d-pawn the protection it needs. }
8... cxd4 { Black realizes that he cannot put more pressure on d4. } 9. cxd4
{ This is the logical recapture. } 9... Bb4+
{ This is the most popular choice. } 10. Bd2 Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2
{ White has a nice edge due to his superior bishop and space advantage. } 11...
Qb4 12. Rc1
{ White can allow Black to take on d2 because the centralized king will not be in danger and will even prove useful in the endgame. }
12... Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2
{ Black has to find a way to activate his light-squared bishop. } *

