[White "Morozevich Variation"]
[Black "Morozevich Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Be7
{ This is known as the Morozevich Variation. Arrising positions are often similar to those in the Closed Variation. }
4. Ngf3 { A simple developing move. } 4... Nf6
{ Black allows e5, when the knight will retreat to d7 with interesting play. }
5. e5 { White saves his pawn by pushing it forward, and gains kingside space. }
5... Nfd7 { From d7, the knight can support a c5 push. } 6. Bd3
{ White develops the bishop to an active square. } 6... c5
{ Black strikes with c5, as usual. } 7. c3
{ As the knight is on d2, c3 can be comfortably played. } 7... b6
{ b6 is an interesting alternative. Black looks to exchange his bad bishop with Ba6. }
8. O-O Ba6 { White cannot avoid the exchange, but Black has lost some time. }
9. Bxa6 Nxa6 10. Re1 { The position is very pleasant for White. } *

