1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4
{ This is known as the Rubinstein Variation. It can also arise from 3. Nc3 instead of Nd2. By trading in the center, Black seems to hand White a nice space advantage. }
4. Nxe4 Nf6
{ Nf6 is rarely played at the master level but very common at lower levels. Black will have some problems because he did not prepare Nf6 with Nd7 first. }
5. Nxf6+ { White takes the knight } 5... Qxf6
{ gxf6 would really expose the Black king. } 6. Nf3 h6 7. Bd3
{ White is focusing on fast development. } 7... Bd6 8. O-O
{ White is in good shape. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Rubinstein Variation"]
[Black "Rubinstein Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4
{ This is known as the Rubinstein Variation. It can also arise from 3. Nc3 instead of Nd2. By trading in the center, Black seems to hand White a nice space advantage. }
4. Nxe4 Bd7
{ This is the main alternative to Nd7. Black prepares to put his bishop on c6 and create a very solid position. }
5. Nf3 { White continues his development. } 5... Bc6 6. Bd3 Nd7 7. O-O
{ White castles. } 7... Ngf6
{ Black hopes that White takes on f6, when the position is fairly equal. } 8.
Ng3 { White avoids a trade and brings his knight to safety. } 8... Be7 9. Re1
{ White's space advantage and more comfortably placed pieces already demonstrate an advantage. }
9... O-O { This is Black's first option. } 10. c3
{ White cements his d4 pawn. Note that Black cannot really play against the d4 pawn because his bishop on c6 blocks his c pawn. }
10... Re8 11. Bf4
{ All of White's pieces are developed and he has a space advantage. } *

