4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ This is the main move, preparing Ngf6. Black certainly has some alternatives however. }
5. Nf3 { Simply developing is very logical } 5... Ngf6 6. Nxf6+
{ White can take on f6. } 6... Nxf6 7. c3
{ This leads to very exciting attacking play. White's score in the database is also fantastic. }
7... c5
{ Black has to find some kind of counterplay. c5 is the way of doing this. } 8.
Be3 { White guards his pawn. } 8... Qc7
{ This is the most popular way for Black to play, getting his queen off the d-file and adding support to the c-pawn. }
9. Ne5 { White centralizes his knight. } 9... a6 10. Qa4+
{ Black cannot respond with b5 because White can play Bxb5+ and a8 is hanging if Black takes on b5. }
10... Nd7 11. Bb5 { White continues to put pressure on Black. } 11... cxd4
{ Allowing Bxd7. } 12. Bxd7+ Bxd7 13. Qxd4
{ With the open d-file and a strong knight on e5, White stands clearly better. Black's king is still in the center. }
*

