[Black "Guimard Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nc6
{ The Guimard Defense is a bit of a surprise weapon, but White can achieve a large advantage if he knows how to handle it. }
4. Ngf3 Nf6 5. e5
{ White closes the position, and Black's knight is inconveniently placed on c6, where it blocks the c-pawn. Usually Black would want to play c5 soon but here that is not possible due to the knight on c6. }
5... Nd7 6. Bd3 { White is developing normally. } 6... Nb4
{ Black attacks his bishop and frees the c-pawn. } 7. Be2
{ Giving up the bishop would not be ideal. } 7... c5
{ Black is able to play c5, pressuring the d4-pawn further. } 8. c3
{ White defends the d4-pawn and hits the knight. } 8... Nc6 9. O-O
{ White brings his king to safety. } 9... cxd4 10. cxd4 f6
{ Black begins the usual plan of undermining White's center pawns. } 11. exf6
Nxf6 12. Nb3 { White has easy play against the e6-pawn. } *

