1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 a6
{ a6 has gained quite a bit of popularity in recent years. Black plays a waiting move and plans to react to White's next choice. }
4. Bd3 { This is a sideline that is actually quite effective. } 4... c5
{ Black strikes in the center. } 5. dxc5 { White opens up the position. } 5...
Bxc5 { Black recaptures the pawn. } 6. Ngf3
{ White's development is very natural. } 6... Nf6
{ The main alternative to Nc6. } 7. O-O Nc6 8. exd5
{ Now Black can either create an isolated pawn or aovid it at the price of giving up the e4-square.. }
8... Nxd5
{ If Black avoids creating an isolated pawn, the e4-square becomes available for White's knight. }
9. Ne4 Be7 10. c4
{ White gains some control of the center and hits the knight on d5. } 10... Nf6
11. Qe2 { Black's position is solid but a bit cramped. } *

